tegies to rationalize the horror and hardship in their lives, practices that maintained citizens' loyalty to the regime during the famine and continue to sustain its rule today. Casting North Koreans as a diverse people with a vast capacity for adaptation rather than as a monolithic entity passively enduring oppression, Marching Through Suffering positions personal history as key to the interpretation of political violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamineszKorea (North) 0aFamineszKorea (North). 0aHuman rightszKorea (North) 0aHuman rightszKorea (North). 0aRefugeeszKorea (North)vBiography. 0aRefugeeszKorea (North)xAttitudes. 0aVictims of faminezKorea (North) 0aVictims of faminezKorea (North). 0zKorea (North)xSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/fahy1713440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231538947.jpg  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK